m/uwyrmbane.showPublicProfile?language=EN>wyrmbane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/12/01 4:34:06 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/oddnfun/wyrmbane_sml.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: heh</span><hr size=1> <br>
I think the key to ToK, is to get it back to what we Believe was the intent of the spell.<br>
<br>
If there are only 40% of the High End Raid Level mobs that use mana to inflict damage, that is fine.  That means 40% of the time it is beneficial but not necessary to have the paladin there.   It is 40% of the time, the paladin has *another* use to the raiding party.<br>
<br>
I believe the intent of the spell was to stop casting outright.  Have a chance to just shut down gates and Cheals, and other spells.  In addition, if VI did put Healing Complete in the game as a mob spell, this silence spell which CAN land on debuffed mobs, is critical, or you end up having to take a mob for 100k+ hp's down to nothing more than once.  <br>
<br>
Yes, mana draining will still be required, but this just helps assure victory. <br>
<br>
The key is to prevent casting of spells with mana.   I believe all spells and abilities are treated like a spell.   A Breath weapon is probably a 0 mana spell, 10 second recast, instant effect.  <br>
<br>
Verant will not change their spell coding for one spell.  They will not restructure Breath attacks, and special abilities as bard songs....which were unaffected by silence.  After all, a bard can sing and run...no spell can do that.<br>
<br>
So, the trick is, how do you code a Mana Casting Spell prevention with little to no coding.<br>
<br>
My initial thought was to add code which did this....<br>
Mob_01_mana_Temp = Mob_01_Mana<br>
Mob_01_Mana = 0.<br>
<br>
Once landed, the mobs mana becomes 0.  When the computer checks, Spell_To_Cast_Mana &lt;= Mob_01 Mana, any spell which has 0 mana will still be &lt;= 0.<br>
<br>
Then, at the end of the spell.<br>
Mob_01_Mana = Mob_01_Mana_Temp.<br>
<br>
I realized that would probably not work with the existing structure of the game and they way spells were coded.  It was then I thought of the absolute option.<br>
<br>
ToK Lands on the mob<br>
<br>
Mob_01_Mana = (-1) * Mob_01_Mana.<br>
<br>
All we did is make the mana less than Zero.  The only additional change, would be to the Spell Check function, so that, <br>
<br>
If not (Spell_Mana_cost = 0 ) then<br>
end if<br>
<br>
so.  With 2 lines of code.  They can make ToK functional as intended.  Any spell based ability with 0 mana would function like normal.  Death touches, Life taps, Harm Touches, Lay hands, Roars, Breath attacks.  Everything.  They are all coded as 0 mana anyhow.  <br>
<br>
At the end of ToK, run the routine again<br>
Mob_01_Mana = (-1) * Mob_01_Mana.<br>
<br>
it now has it's mana back.  <br>
<br>
Yes, I didn't think about Mana sieving the mob during this time.  Doing this would add mana to the mob.  Not sure what a good method to code that would be....other than<br>
If ToK then<br>
   adjust_mana_for_Tok (Mana drained)  - would make the mana drained a positive...small function<br>
   Adjust_mana of mob(mana drained) - would add to the negative value of the mobs mana, draining it from them.<br>
<br>
Just my thoughts.  Not sure if that is a viable thing for VI to add to their code.   I would expect since it is C++, they would only need to add those 2 Function calls to their current spell routine, and it would work.    However, without looking at the actual code, I do not know.<br>
<br>
Wyrmbane<br>
<br>
ps.  this is all based on something I read from the developers a long time ago, which was &quot;if you are thinking of a change to something in EQ, you have to ask yourself, can it be done with minimal or no coding&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
